snippet.textDisplay: Thank you for sharing this video, very helpful!  Please try to use latex-free elastics or rubber bands if you are donating these masks to hospital workers.  Regular elastics are made of natural latex, which is a sap from the hevea tree.  About 17% of healthcare workers are allergic to latex because of the gloves they wear and their symptoms can worsen if their skin is in contact with latex.  It’s a cumulative allergy, like bee stings, so the symptoms can become severe overnight when you’re exposed to latex.  Once you develop this allergy it’s for life and there’s no treatment or cure.  It’s best to avoid wearing latex / NRL gloves too if you can.  The safe ones are NITRILE or VINYL gloves.  Stay safe 🙌

snippet.textDisplay:
Very effective homemade masks:
A mask can be made from a large plastic bottle so that it not only protects your mouth and nose, but also your eyes. You cut off the top and bottom of the bottle and then cut it lengthwise to open it. If you wear glasses, you can make two holes so that the things that the glasses have that go behind the ear (sorry, I do not speak English and I do not know what they are called hahaha) come out of the mask and you can put it on. If you do not wear glasses you can glue the top to a hat or tiara. These types of masks are very cheap, but most important: effective, because they isolate your entire face so that you not only do not get the virus, but also not accidentally infect other people.
After you used this kind of mask, you can clean them and use it again, this does not happen with the chinstrap because after a while they absorb droplets of saliva and they no longer work.

Well I do not know how many people read this comment but I hope it have been useful to someone.

Sending you good energy from the other side of the world!! and stay at home as much as you can!!! 💕🇺🇾

Además luego las limpias y las puedes volver a usar, esto no ocurre con los barbijos porque luego de un tiempo van absorbiendo las gotitas de saliva y ya no funcionan.

snippet.textDisplay:
One 2015 study found that cloth masks only blocked 3% of particles, compared with medical masks (which stopped 56% of particles) and N95s (protective against 99.9% of particles, the study found). Healthcare workers wearing cloth masks were significantly more likely to be infected with flu-like illness.

A 2013 study found that cloth masks made from cotton T-shirts, pillowcases, or tea towels should be used only as a last resort — they only filtered out a third of the aerosols blocked by a surgical mask — though it was found to be "better than no protection."

Common fabrics have pores too large for viruses, that are about 100 nanometer in diameter, and most airborne droplets that contain viruses. In contrast, the pore sizes of knitted fabrics are often measured in micrometers, which are 1000 times larger than nanometers.

According to the textbook Physico-chemical aspects of Textile Coloration, cotton pores tend to exceed 10-20 micrometers, or 10,000 to 20,000 nanometers.

snippet.textDisplay: When I tried to narrow some elastic I had, it kept fraying along the cut end, releasing the rubber strands. Instead, I ran a zigzag stitch along one edge, then cut it just beyond the other edge of the stitch, so it bound the cut edge and kept it from fraying. I narrowed some 9.5mm wide elastic with a 4.5mm stitch down each edge: https://i.imgur.com/VphN2SN.jpg There can still be some fraying, but it stops at the edge of the zigzag.
